          "type": "text",
          "text": "Circuit is live! Here's everything you need to know:\n\n---\n\n## 🔌 Wiring Table\n\n| Arduino Pin | Wire Color | → Component | Description |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **D2** | Red | → R_A → Display seg A | Segment A |\n| **D3** | Orange | → R_B → Display seg B | Segment B |\n| **D4** | Yellow | → R_C → Display seg C | Segment C |\n| **D5** | Green | → R_D → Display seg D | Segment D |\n| **D6** | Blue | → R_E → Display seg E | Segment E |\n| **D7** | Purple | → R_F → Display seg F | Segment F |\n| **D8** | White | → R_G → Display seg G | Segment G |\n| **GND** | Black | → Display GND | Common cathode ground |\n| **D9** | Cyan | → Button pin A | Button input |\n| **GND** | Black | → Button pin B | Button ground |\n\nAll 7 segments use a **220Ω series resistor** each.\n\n---\n\n## 🧠 Sketch Summary\n\n- **Button on D9** with `INPUT_PULLUP` — no external resistor needed\n- **Edge detection**: only counts on the *falling edge* (press, not hold)\n- **50ms debounce** to avoid false triggers\n- **Count wraps**: 0 → 1 → ... → 9 → 0\n- `showDigit(n)` uses an `if/else` chain to drive the 7 segments for each digit\n\n---\n\n## ⚡ Power Budget\n\n| Item | Current |\n|---|---|\n| Each lit segment (5V − 2V) / 220Ω | ~13.6 mA |\n| Max segments ON at once (digit 8 = 7 segs) | ~95 mA |\n| Per Arduino output pin (1 segment) | ✅ 13.6 mA < 20 mA limit |\n| Button pin (INPUT_PULLUP, no load) | ~0 mA |\n| **Total max board draw** | **~95 mA** |\n\n> ✅ Well within Arduino Uno limits (200 mA total I/O). Each pin stays safely under the 20 mA per-pin limit.\n\n---\n\n**How to use:** Press the button once to increment the display. It counts **0 → 9**, then wraps back to **0**. 🎉"
        }
      ]
